text: @JCStrachan876 @SimonKuepper Traffic bottlenecks cause the cars to slow; potholes cause the traffic to swerve.
@SimonKuepper But it is the micro GPS data -- braking and swerving -- that will reveal the location and size of the potholes. Would Google Maps traffic data have that?

@islandsurveyor @taychin Everyone has an incentive to install the app since, by providing the data for the roads that you drive on, you are in effect "voting" for the prioritizing of the roads relevant to your commutes.

No. Under my system, users don't have to do anything after installing the app. Everything else happens automatically. Moreover, by tracking the number of vehicles that drive past any particular pothole, the algorithim knows which potholes are affecting the most traffic. https://t.co/UtywcmWE0o

App idea.

App detects when you're in a moving vehicle and tracks its movements.

In wifi, data uploaded to a server. An algorithim analyses all the tracked data (braking, swerves) to work out where the potholes are and how many vehicles affected.

Result? priority potholes.
